// A bare `import { + }` is gated by `is_operator_name`: `+` is recognized as an
// operator spelling (so this is NOT the "is not a builtin" fallthrough), but `+`
// is special — it must be imported as `wrapping_add as +`. This pins that
// `is_operator_name` classifies `+` as an operator; a port that dropped `+` from
// the operator set would instead produce the generic "is not a builtin" error.
import { + } from builtins;

fn main() {}
--- errors ---
error: the "+" operator has no bare form; pick a semantics and import it aliased, e.g. `wrapping_add as +` or `saturating_add as +` from builtins
 --> ./tests/cases/imports/err_bare_plus_operator.aipl:1:1
